<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05034a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05034a">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05034a"> 34(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> in default of authority for what / he dares to promise he is fain / to express what he desires O / holy presumption! (S Martin / promises to serve Satan)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;What sayest thou, O wretched one!&rsquo; cried the Saint. &lsquo;To thee, even to thee, wouldst thou but cease to tempt men, wouldst thou but repent of thy crimes, even now, when the Day of Judgement is at hand, I, confiding in our Lord Jesus Christ, would dare promise thee His mercy.&rsquo; &lsquo;<mark>Oh, holy presumption!</mark>&rsquo; cries an old writer, speaking of this legend. &lsquo;<mark>In default of authority for what he dares to promise, he is fain to express what he desires</mark>.&rsquo; <small> Margaret Maitland, <a name="MMLL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MMLL"><cite title="source">Life and Legends of St. Martin of Tours (316-397)</cite></a> (1908) 48</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02033h" href="c02all.htm#c02033h">VI.C.02:033(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
